<P><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mr Guy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I'm curious what happens when you agro mobs.  Is the distance to mob check done server side or client side?<P>I remember there used to be (and maybe still is) a bug where the faction wouldn't get loaded very quickly when you zone, so you had a couple seconds of safetly where everything would con indifferently.  That makes me think that with some considerably difficulty, and with a decent understand of how the memory structure works you could make yourself indifferent to any given mob, and walk around unmolested in any zone.<P>Thoughts?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Astro</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><BR>Nope, this was done temporarily to allow for slower computers.<P>It was server-side, and they removed this feature altogether a long time ago.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mr Guy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well the support is gone, but that doesn't change the original question premise.  What happens when something agros? Does the client initiate or does the server?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Astro</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><BR>0% of faction is client side, always has been.<P>0% of mob behavior is client side, always has been.<P>The server controls the mobs, in every respect;  client just shows the graphics.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Rahvin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Distance/proximity agro however could be controlled client side with some clever packet editing. Since the client sends positional updates to the server, and mobs have known agro radiuses as well as face direction, etc, you could avoid sending any packets (wouldn't neccessarily have to be the packets), or modify them in order to remove you getting agroed.<P>If that was offtopic too bad =/ Only representation of faction [impact] would be able to change on the client.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">LincolnsAura</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">what if you edited where the client told the server where you are standing at.... couldnt you traverse a zone without gathering agro? but i guess after that you would have to release the edit and people would see you pop on the other side of the zone.... <P>|_ /\</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Astro</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><BR>Forget the idea of editing packets.<P>It's just not gonna happen.<P>First you would have to decrypt them.  Next you would have to break whatever scheme they use as a checksum.  <P>It just isn't worth the effort, considering any limited benefit you could gain.<P>For any scenario you could imagine that would require packet editing, it would be 100 times easier just to trick your client into sending whatever packet you want it to.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mr Guy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Actually, in order to do a similiar thing, you could simple set up a sorta selective firewall that calculates agro range and blocks packets briefly while your client runs through.  It'd look like a lag warp on their side and your client would never know the difference.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Astro</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><BR>Simple? <P>Wow, make anything even remotely akin to what you describe and I'll bow down to you.<P>Why not just pull the plug on your connection until you get where you're going?<P>Works fine, you get 20+ seconds to run around.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mr Guy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The logging and determining agro part I know how to do.  The blocking packets part I don't.  ::shrug:: I guess a windows port of ShowEq interested me enough to learn the first part, but ZoneAlarm is already free...</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Casper</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mr. Guy --<P>To block packets - search for everywhere that sendto() is called from w/in the client.  You can put a breakpoint in sendto() and selectively let only those go that you want based on size; e.g. basically return from sendto w/o sending the packet.  Or, you can trace up the stack to find where the packet originates and block it from there - your choice and both methods work.<P>If you choose to block the packets in sendto() then, depending on the packet you're blocking, the client may try to resend over and over again.  At least you know how to do it quickly.<P>If you wanted to write in C then you may be able to do an old winsock.dll trick I did when Rainbow6 first came out.  Basically create a duplicate winsock and put it in your directory path so you get loaded instead of the real winsock.  Then your winsock loads the real one to trampoline the calls to it for the real functionality. At least you can write in C and you only need to export what the EQ Client imports out of the dll.<P>I ran into a small problem when I first tried that - then I lost interest.  I think someone who wants to put in a little time can end up with something...<P></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
